	<h3 class="piece_header"> How to change your life in 30 days? </h3>		
	<p> 
<strong> An immersion technique to start new. </strong> <br> <br>

June 24th. 2016. I had recently moved out of the startup I co-founded. I had no clue what to do. I did not have an idea. Or a team. Most importantly I was burnt out. Life seemed really big and tough and scary. I had a lot of questions but no answer. Insecure, on the verge of depression, isolated, clueless. This was my state.
<br> <br>

<strong> How do you change your life? </strong> By changing yourself. <br> <br>

<strong> How do you change yourself?</strong> By changing your actions <br> <br>

<strong> How do you change your actions? </strong> By changing the way you think, by changing and testing your assumptions, inferences, conclusion. By validating the mental frameworks you use to arrive at decisions. By being clear on what basis you take decisions, what are your triggers, what are your strengths, what are your weaknesses,
<br> <br>

<strong> How do you change the way you think? </strong> I did by reading, writing and content creation.
<br> <br>

I started writing my blog here at medium with a promise to myself that I will write and publish 1 blog every day.(Till then I had written a total of 8 articles in the previous 1 year). For the next one month. 30 blogs. Simple, only one thing, no other constraint — like I should get thousands of shares or build a following. Just pure writing, whatever I can think of, without any expectation.
<br> <br>

I took my journal and started writing. One article after another. First I wrote whatever I can think of. I started to write about things which I was curious and frustrated about — like how to get out of a “low” state, how to start creating, how to inspire myself, how to find a life philosophy that could help motivate myself, what is the right attitude to carry, how to discover and improve upon potential, anything that meant life and death to me — finding the answer to these questions was the only way I could get out of the “low” phase I was in. Anything I can learn, anything that improved my life, I wrote about it.<br> <br>

Initial days I didn’t know what to write. I would just stare at my computer screen without typing anything. Then I took my pen and journal. I found writing much more easier [many of us have been first taught to write before typing, so writing by hand is much more intuitive and easy]. I wanted to an out from reality, so I immersed myself into the books. The more I read the more I could write [this is an universal phenomena, many good writers are voracious readers] <br> <br>

I started reading. Voraciously. I downloaded a bunch of books. And bought a few. Books on cognitive psychology, thinking. Anything that would give me a clue about what is happening in my head. How to get clear about anything in life. How to find why I am again and again getting warped all the time, unable to do anything productive.
<br> <br>

The first book was The Mindset by Carol Dweck. The next one was Thinking fast and slow, by Daniel Kahneman. The moment I started reading, I was into it. I started to think through my life situations in perspective to understand how am taking decisions, how am arriving at conclusions, the assumptions I have — that is what exactly a good book will do to you, give you clue about who you really are.
<br> <br>

<strong> Learning #1 </strong> <br> <br>
I got into a momentum, for the first time in so many months. I read half the time and wrote the remaining half. I read books, blogs, anything on topics am interested in and then wrote about it. I learnt that CURIOSITY is the biggest guidance to doing anything. It makes learning anything new fairly interesting.

<strong> Learning #2 </strong> <br> <br>
I start writing a lot, like 4–5 articles a day, all on my journal. Then I would sit and write and edit on my computer notepad and publish. I just focused writing one article, then the other. After being stuck for some time, I suddenly felt like the flood gates have been opened. Words started flowing. I learnt that focusing on the next smallest possible action is the key to momentum. I also understood that what matters is what all you can do right now, at this moment.

<strong> Learning #3 </strong> <br> <br>
This reading and writing improved my thinking process greatly. I started seeing things clearly. After a week, I decided I just did not want to write, but write for a bigger cause than me. I focused on only one thing — creating value through my writing. Even if one person will read and get something valuable from my articles to improve his or her life, that is enough. I focused only on one reader at a time. I learnt that what is important in life is giving — not taking. You give more than you take. Create value and put it out there.

<strong> Learning #4 </strong> <br> <br>
I slowly started writing stuff that brought out the pain me. I learnt that your work gets transformed only when you bring your pain to your creations. You face your pain and translate them into words and words into a story. Your real work shows your struggle and pain. I was able to get closure on my emotional problems this way. Lot of problems that were scaring me, that I was hiding in the closet, I let them go and put it out for the entire world to see. I shared my biggest fears through my articles. And I felt like a bird released from its cage.

<strong> Learning #5 </strong> <br> <br>
One month got over, I had written 52 articles — some days I had published more than one. I documented the whole process by which I wrote the articles, what I gained. I learnt that by objectively looking at your past actions, you could learn more than you otherwise do. I found out what I am doing right, what I am doing wrong, where do I stand in terms of blogging, quality of writing, and started thinking of ideas to get more people to read my articles so that I can create value for more, I can touch more lives. I learnt that the bigger part of trying anything is about losing shame. Once you shed this, everything else follows.
<br> <br>

Fast forward to today, I have written 120 articles across Medium, Quora. I developed a following on instagram based on my travel to rural India and little known places. So far few of my articles have been guest posted in third party website. I recently got noticed and appreciated for an article I wrote on LinkedIn.I am consulting now with startups on their content marketing and strategy (an opportunity I purely got out of my writing and content creation). The fight is far from over. But Writing has literally changed my life in 30 days.
<br> <br>

Common belief is that we think and then act. I realized that there is another form of thinking — through an action. Many ideas I got only when I was writing. Our brain muscles are flexible that way. Our actions induce our thinking and vice versa.
<br> <br>

You can change your life by writing (its an easy and simple place to start). But you can also start a youtube channel. Or create a mobile app. Or go about surveying people and doing research about consumer behavior. Whatever it is, immerse yourself. For the next 30 days. Learn as much you can, practice the craft as much as you can.
<br> <br>

The only way you can change your life is by practicing a craft and creating. Because the only thing that matters in life is creation.
	</p>
